Latin America's Locust Years
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
This is hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have gone nowhere in the last twenty years.
Capital has been sold and national debts have been massively increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
Ces années ont vraiment été mangées par les sauterelles.
Au cours des 20 dernières années, la croissance annuelle du PNB par habitant en Amérique Latine a atteint la moyenne de 0,35 %.
A cette vitesse, une économie mettrait 200 années à doubler.
En Asie, le niveau de vie double chaque décennie .
Avec une croissance tellement anémique, comment l'Amérique Latine peut-elle espérer rivaliser dans le commerce mondial à part à travers une hausse des salaires toujours timide ?
Economic stagnation is the result of a bad government, not of bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
First, in the rush towards privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been put up for sale.
For a brief moment, the sale of capital helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues derived from privatization have produced little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets has been accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national purchasers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency remains a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reforms have not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital produced an effect of wealth, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be in place to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being trampled, property rights are being questioned, and an effort at arbitrary and even more corrupt redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and her team, who conduct opinion polls in the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already started to flee - even though the elections are only in a few months.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this may well prove to be ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the financial result economically speaking, because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat 1970s of OPEC - years it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking holidays in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40 percent, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are pro-market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half of that of Brazil.
But with growth in China's coastal region at about 15% per year, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first due to the massive flow of foreign direct investments and the imminent advantages of accession to the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to unravel: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but these times are largely past.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may resemble a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
